Thank you. I see Amelia had asked a question over on Slido. Let me just pull this up into the

00:06:12.959 --> 00:06:19.440
screen. And it was, could you share more about the multi-year process for building this out,

00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:23.839
things like key milestones or unexpected challenges and how you dealt with them?

00:06:25.839 --> 00:06:32.160
Yeah, I think this was an interesting project because we did inherit it. This was,

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:38.720
as I think I mentioned in the presentation, it was a previously built out tool by a third party.

00:06:39.359 --> 00:06:45.279
And we wanted to replicate that in-house. At the time we replicated that, that was very early on

00:06:45.279 --> 00:06:53.119
when I started it at Suffolk, we had a different tool suite. We didn't have Posit at that point,

00:06:53.119 --> 00:06:58.160
actually. And so we built it out using a different tool set that admittedly was not as

00:06:58.160 --> 00:07:06.559
replicable. And so we had sort of our version one, which was building it out using, I would say,

00:07:06.559 --> 00:07:14.000
an old data stack relative to what we have now. And I would say the key challenges were mostly,

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:21.200
I would say, about the distribution of our findings. That was certainly an unexpected challenge

00:07:21.440 --> 00:07:27.359
of our findings. That was certainly an unexpected challenge or more challenging than I thought,

00:07:27.359 --> 00:07:33.440
in that maybe the way we presented it was not, maybe came off a little more combative than we

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:39.760
anticipated, not because we were trying to call project teams out for their risk, but it was

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:44.160
being interpreted that way. And I could absolutely understand why it was being interpreted that way.

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:52.720
So for us, the challenge in moving into our newer version of it was mostly around

00:07:52.720 --> 00:07:59.519
the presentation of it and how we can provide as much value as possible where project teams

00:07:59.519 --> 00:08:04.720
see us as being a resource for them and not trying to point a finger at them. So I would

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:10.640
say that was the unexpected challenge and sort of how we've tailored the presentation

00:08:10.959 --> 00:08:12.720
of the data to reflect that.

00:08:16.559 --> 00:08:21.920
Yeah, I think that comes up a lot in some of the data science Hangouts, too, that it's actually

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:28.320
some of the human-centric problems and working together with stakeholders that can come up

00:08:30.959 --> 00:08:37.200
in these workflows. Would you have any, I guess, recommendations or tips for us,

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:43.039
or somebody who's doing something similar and rolling out a new project to business stakeholders?

00:08:44.719 --> 00:08:49.359
Well, I would say it's just important to understand their point of view as much as

00:08:49.359 --> 00:08:57.679
possible. And so I think just having a partner stakeholder who is as invested in the end goal

00:08:57.679 --> 00:09:03.679
as possible and getting their opinion as quickly as possible. I think the biggest problem that

00:09:03.679 --> 00:09:08.719
would probably run up is if you build something out, invested a lot of time in it, and it ends

00:09:08.719 --> 00:09:12.799
up being a lot different than they would expect or presents a different message than they would

00:09:12.799 --> 00:09:17.760
want it to. And then you have to go back and iterate from the beginning. Whereas if you

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:23.200
started out with something basic, show a generic template of kind of what you're doing and then

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:29.280
get feedback as quickly as possible. I think it's being open and humble to the feedback that you get

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:36.479
and being comfortable with any criticism or any information that they can give you.

00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:42.880
Absolutely. Blake, do you have anything you wanted to add to that?

00:09:44.479 --> 00:09:48.719
I think Max hit on one of our biggest challenges. I guess another side of that,

00:09:48.719 --> 00:09:52.799
particularly to the safety model, if you think about it, we're trying to predict something then

00:09:52.799 --> 00:09:59.440
that we're actively trying to prevent. Traditional metrics of success are, we're

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:05.039
not going to run an A-B test on a safety model and not give a project team an idea that they're

00:10:05.039 --> 00:10:10.559
going to be at risk. So it does present challenges that the predictions of what we're doing,

00:10:10.559 --> 00:10:14.640
hopefully, ultimately all turned out to be wrong, that there are no incidents on a project. So

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:20.320
how we actually evaluate the success of this is, as Max alluded to, less the success of the model,

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:28.080
but more just acceptance by the broader Suffolk team about safety as a cultural pillar.

00:10:30.479 --> 00:10:37.359
Yeah, that's a great point. That's something that I struggle with sometimes with customer stories

00:10:37.359 --> 00:10:44.479
that I'm writing, is trying to get to what might be the ROI metric that I can highlight in that

00:10:44.479 --> 00:10:50.640
story. And it sounds like with it being cultural, it's a little bit harder to measure in this

00:10:50.640 --> 00:11:00.239
example. Yeah, that's right. You have to buy in from the start that safety is, incidents are a

00:11:00.239 --> 00:11:05.919
risk and safety is something we're going to be focused on regardless of whether we have a model

00:11:05.919 --> 00:11:10.880
or not. And this is just a tool to help us concentrate where we put most of our effort.

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:20.239
Yeah. I see an anonymous question that came in, which was, have your buy-to-build decisions

