your observations around, you know, more project teams and being more consistent with that,

00:22:03.520 --> 00:22:12.640
just as an example. Great, thank you. I see, I think there's one other question I hadn't

00:22:13.359 --> 00:22:18.000
covered yet. And it was an anonymous one on Slido that said,

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:24.400
from a less experienced data scientist who recognizes the value of Posit workflows,

00:22:24.400 --> 00:22:28.640
what did your personal experience look like initially exploring these tools?

00:22:30.959 --> 00:22:37.439
Yeah, I mean, initially exploring these tools, I would say, you know, I would say my initial

00:22:37.439 --> 00:22:43.839
data science experience was more in Python than in R. And so, you know, you know, certainly,

00:22:43.839 --> 00:22:48.000
since Blake has come on, and, you know, a little bit before then, I've gotten more comfortable

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:53.520
with R over time. And, you know, so I, my data science experience initially was more in, you

00:22:53.520 --> 00:23:00.160
know, the Python realm, the scikit-learn, you know, sort of side of things and looking at the R

00:23:00.160 --> 00:23:07.520
suite, specifically, like the tidy models flow, it all had endpoints that are, you know, points

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:12.800
that really complemented each other, you know, not just building out a model, but how to how to go

00:23:12.800 --> 00:23:18.400
through finding the best one and all the hyper parameter tuning that goes along with that,

00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:23.520
and then how to actually, you know, as it specifies to Posit, how to how to actually deploy it and to

00:23:23.520 --> 00:23:31.439
do it more easily. And so to me, my experience was, it certainly seemed a lot easier and simpler

00:23:31.439 --> 00:23:39.599
to go from a starting point and make a make a model deploy it and then have a process for inference

00:23:39.599 --> 00:23:46.319
that made it as replicable as as possible without as much error while reducing, you know, effort

00:23:46.319 --> 00:23:49.040
later on to actually feed data into the model.

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:59.359
Thank you. I think there might just be now one more question we hadn't gotten to, but I know this

00:23:59.920 --> 00:24:05.359
touches on something you had talked about already around working with stakeholders, but

00:24:05.920 --> 00:24:11.839
Yumito asked, did you get any disputes from the project site team based on the model project

00:24:11.839 --> 00:24:19.199
rating prediction? All the time. Yeah. And I, you know, I, you know, they know their projects

00:24:19.199 --> 00:24:24.800
so much better than we do. And so we would be, you know, you know, I think it would be faulty

00:24:24.800 --> 00:24:30.000
of us to say that, you know, we know, you know, more about their project than they do. That said,

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:33.920
I think we also look at the project from a different perspective as them. I think they're

00:24:33.920 --> 00:24:39.439
very focused on, you know, what's happening on a day to day basis, and they are aware of their

00:24:39.439 --> 00:24:44.560
project risks. And so in their mind, I would say sometimes they're, you know, implementing

00:24:46.079 --> 00:24:50.640
strategies to mitigate that risk, but we are, we're merely calling out the fact that there

00:24:50.640 --> 00:24:54.400
is risk. And so sometimes I think there is a mistranslation of what we're trying to show

00:24:55.280 --> 00:25:02.479
versus what they think we're trying to show. But yeah, to answer the question, yes. And, you know,

00:25:02.479 --> 00:25:07.599
we're trying to be as understanding of that as possible and trying to get that feedback and,

00:25:07.599 --> 00:25:13.920
you know, hopefully continue to evolve this and make it as, you know, as useful as possible for

00:25:13.920 --> 00:25:19.599
them. Yeah. Just one other comment on that. I think it touches on the previous question. I think

00:25:19.599 --> 00:25:24.400
that feedback, I think helped us drive some of the changes Max made where it's, you know, I think the

00:25:24.400 --> 00:25:29.040
first version, it was all projects objectively against one another, whereas the real value is

00:25:29.040 --> 00:25:33.199
a project measured against itself. So it's relative risk to how it had been previously

00:25:33.439 --> 00:25:38.719
is really the value we're trying to drive. So, you know, some projects are just inherently high

00:25:38.719 --> 00:25:43.760
risk. So, you know, there'll always be higher than the other projects. So really understanding

00:25:43.760 --> 00:25:48.400
how it relates to itself over time is the value we think we can add with the model.

